    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - DRIVETRAIN FAILURE ANALYSIS - AXLE COMPONENTS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcsubsec>
        <title>AXLE COMPONENTS</title>
        <svcproc svcproctype="IDcomponent" graphiccount="7">
            <title>RING AND PINION SETS</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Gear teeth surface fused. A charred appearance indicates an overheated condition. Metal
                    lifted off the pinion and fused to the ring gear teeth (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1300239">Figure 39</hotlnk>). This is due to lack of lubricant.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1300239" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1300239" filename="../figg13/G1300239.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 39. Gear Teeth Surface Fused</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Shock load. Teeth as shown in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1300240">Figure 40</hotlnk>were in mesh with the pinion and were subjected to an
                    instantaneous shock load. The fracture is rough and looks crystalline.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1300240" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1300240" filename="../figg13/G1300240.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 40. Shock Load</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Spalling and pitting. Flakes of metal have broken off the tooth surface to create a
                    spalled condition (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1300241">Figure 41</hotlnk>). This failure started with pitting at the tooth root
                    and advanced to spalling at the tooth working surface. It is usually caused by continuous
                    overloading.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1300241" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1300241" filename="../figg13/G1300241.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 41. Spalling and Pitting</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Flank cracking. This type of fatigue failure will first develop cracks that run the
                    length of the tooth face. Once the cracks appear, the metal between them begins to flake away and
                    failure occurs rapidly (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1300242">Figure 42</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1300242" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1300242" filename="../figg13/G1300242.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 42. Flank Cracking</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Drive pinion fatigue failure. A torsional and bending force caused the pinion in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1300243">Figure 43</hotlnk>to fail. The failure was probably due to operational
                    overloads or a shock load.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1300243" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1300243" filename="../figg13/G1300243.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 43. Drive Pinion Fatigue Failure</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Root beam fatigue.
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1300244">Figure 44</hotlnk>shows typical root beam bending fatigue beach marks at
                    the roots of all damaged teeth. If the remaining teeth are in good condition, the probable cause was
                    a shock load.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1300244" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1300244" filename="../figg13/G1300244.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 44. Root Beam Fatigue</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Crows foot pattern. This pattern on gear teeth is characteristic of wear caused by
                    improper lubricants or lubricants with depleted additives (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1300245">Figure 45</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1300245" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1300245" filename="../figg13/G1300245.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0"/>
                    <caption>Figure 45. Crows Foot Pattern</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
    </svcsubsec>
